Vaccines against SARS and MERS have been tested in nonhuman animal models.
As of 2020, there is no cure or protective vaccine for SARS that has been shown to be safe and effective in humans.
According to research papers published in 2005 and 2006, the identification and development of new vaccines and drugs to treat SARS is a priority for governments and public health agencies around the world. In addition, proven vaccines for MERS also do not exist.
As MERS becomes prevalent, existing SARS research is believed to be a useful template for developing vaccines and therapies against MERS-CoV infections.
