The World Health Organization announced on February 11, 2020 that the official name of the disease is "COVID-19".
WHO leader Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus explained that CO stands for corona, VI for virus, D for disease, and 19 for when the outbreak was first identified: 31 December 2019.
The name was chosen to avoid reference to a specific geographic location (e.g. China), an animal species, or a group of people, in line with international recommendations for naming aimed at preventing stigmatization. The virus that caused COVID-19 was named severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
The WHO also uses the "Covid-19 virus" and the "virus responsible for COVID-19" in public communications.
Both diseases and viruses are commonly referred to as "coronaviruses".
